			<td class="BoardRowA" colspan=2 width="83%"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Date Posted:</span> 
			11/27/01 9:15am 
			<span style="font-weight: bold;">Subject:</span> Harder to play &quot;evil&quot; on a roleplay server?			
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr valign=top>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				I am starting this thread because of a thread started by Goldleaf. The thread she started was really intellignet and made me think about how I am roleplaying and how some of the situations that I have run into on this server affected my enjoyment here. <br>  <br> I am going to start with a little bit of history. <br>  <br> First, in my 20 some years of table top RPG's I have never roleplayed in an Evil campaign. Sure my character was taken over by evil forces and made to do there bidding every now and then (who hasn't right?) and I have been a  DM/GM/Storyteller an controlled the evil forces my friends have encountered... but I have never played an evil character through a long term campaign. <br>  <br> Ok history class is now over. <br>  <br> I am roleplaying my evil character here on FV by using evil adjectives and metaphors in my casual conversations and making good use of /cackle and /grin. But while I am trying to roleplay here on FV, I do have a rule I have always followed. That is, if a light race person or group is trying to negotiate or resolve an issue that will affect both parties I will do my best to work with them. <br>  <br> I do this mainly because its a game. From a roleplay point of view its not so far fetched. There are many examples in literature, movies and other pop culture media where the good guys had to team up with the bad guys to achieve a common objective. <br>  <br> The trouble is, if folks don't try to work out the &quot;common&quot; goals with each other (basically anything that affect safety/play nice rules/general enjoyment) were going to have a lot of difficulty on this server. <br>  <br> To goldleaf's point, this doesnt mean that every druid HAS to port everyone that asks. What I think it does mean is that if a dark group approaches a light group about a camp, the play nice rules should apply and not, &quot;Piss off Dark Elf! There is no room here for the likes of you!&quot; <br>  <br> But people are inclined to respond like that because of the &quot;Evil&quot; race. Thats no longer roleplaying. Thats just not playing nice. Infact, its entirely likely that the dark group could /petition and have a GM enforce the play nice rules. How is that roleplaying? (last time I roleplayed gods didn't come down from the heavens to resolve desputes over who is going to take what orc camp). I think this makes it really hard to play (not roleplay) an evil race on this server. <br>  <br> Anyone else have any thoughts on this subject? <br>  <br>  <br>  <br> 
						<p><span class="SignatureTitle">-----signature-----</span>
						<div class="SignatureText">
						Quillion <br> 
						</div>
							

