		<tr valign=top>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				I replied to this earlier, and the boards crashed and my reply got lost.  *sigh* <br>  <br> But here goes the revision of what I said. <br>  <br> First of all, I'm a guy, but that's okay. <br>  <br> Second, in this environment, &quot;evil&quot; is played vis a vis the environment, as is &quot;good&quot;.  It is a mistake to think that &quot;evil can only be done if there's PvP&quot;.  A corollary of this logic is that &quot;good&quot; equals &quot;pacifism&quot;, and that's just utter nonsense.  One cannot have valor and glory without battle.  A similar logic would dictate that &quot;good can only be done if there's PvP&quot;.  After all, a Paladin of the Lightbringer should, by all rights, smite any Necromancer or Shadowknight he sees, no questions asked.  You can play &quot;evil&quot; against the NPCs--killing elven slaves in Crushbone, for example, while your &quot;good&quot; counterparts kill the orc legionnaires.  Granted, it'd be interesting to have an enviroment that included FV's ruleset and PvP, but that would also attract the grief players unless it were carefully crafted.  (If it were up to me, Neutrals wouldn't be able to attack Goods, and vice-versa, although they couldn't help each other either, and Evils would be able to attack one another as well as everyone else.  This leads me to my next point...) <br>  <br> Third, I did play in my partner's AD&amp;D campaign for ten years, and one of the parties that we had going (and that was most popular with the players) was an evil party.  However, it only stuck together because the Cavalier (essentially a Shadowknight) in charge, Bianca, was (charismatic/despotic).  My character, a necromancer and the second-highest level character in the party and apprentice to Bloodstone, sliced off the ears of one of the other characters in the party because he attempted to steal something from her vault.  When Bianca wasn't present, things quickly degenerated and people fought with one another, sometimes leading to bad feelings among the players.  (I'm not sure if there's really a point here, or if this is just nostalgic.) <br>  <br> Fourth, it seems to me, that in the example that appears to have spawned this discussion, you and the Paladin in question were essentially speaking two different languages, even though you were both speaking Human (I presume).  It seems, from what you related, he wanted to resolve the dispute over the camp through roleplaying, and you wanted to resolve it through OOC means.  It may have been better to have /duelled him over the camp, with the loser going elsewhere.  Or simply saying &quot;Foolish knight, I cannot be held responsible for anything that might occur as a result of your folly.  You have been warned.&quot;  Or something to that effect. <br>  <br> Lastly, I believe that kill-stealing is a violation of the Play Nice Policies.  I haven't read them in some time, but I have /petitioned repeat offenders and GMs have acted upon it. <br>  <br> Lasgalen		

			</td>
		</tr>
